Name: speak
Description: Local text-to-speech tools using the system voice engine (pyttsx3).
Version: 1.0

Overview:
The speak toolset provides simple text-to-speech on this machine. It can list
installed voices and speak text using a chosen voice and optional rate/volume
settings. This runs locally (no network calls) and uses the OS voice engine.

Commands:
- list_voices
  Returns a list of available voices with fields:
  - id: engine-specific voice id
  - name: human-readable name
  - languages: list of language tags (if provided by engine)

- speak
  Speak text using an optional voice id/name and optional rate/volume.
  Parameters:
  - text (string, required): The text to speak.
  - voice_id (string, optional): Voice id or voice name from list_voices.
  - rate (integer, optional): Speech rate (engine default is usually 200).
  - volume (number, optional): Volume from 0.0 to 1.0.

Usage Examples:
- list_voices

- speak "Hello world"

- speak "Good morning" voice_id="Microsoft David Desktop" rate=180 volume=0.9

- speak "Bonjour" voice_id="TTS_MS_FR-FR_HORTENSE_11.0" rate=170

Behavior Notes:
- If voice_id is omitted, the engine default voice is used.
- If rate/volume are omitted, engine defaults are used.
- If voice_id does not match any voice, the default voice is used.
- The command blocks until speech finishes.

Error Handling:
- If the local TTS engine (pyttsx3) is not installed, the tool will raise an error.
- If the tools directory is missing or voices cannot be enumerated, list_voices may return an empty list.

Security & Privacy:
- Speech runs locally on this device; no text is sent over the network.

Dependencies:
- pyttsx3 (local TTS engine)
